    intro: "Mount Abu is Rajasthan's only hill station — and it earns its singular status. At 1,220 m in the Aravalli range near the Gujarat border, it is green, cool, and surrounded by dense forests that feel completely different from the arid plains below. Its principal attraction — the Dilwara Jain Temples — contains some of the finest marble carvings in the world: 1,000-year-old sculptures so detailed that the stone appears to have been worked with thread rather than chisel. At 780 km from Delhi via Jaipur and Udaipur, Mount Abu is best combined with a Rajasthan multi-city trip — or done as a standalone long-weekend overnight drive.",
    bestTime: { period: "November–March", description: "November to March is ideal — 10–25°C, clear skies, and the forests are green from monsoon. March brings the Shivratri Fair, one of Rajasthan's largest tribal festivals at Mount Abu's Brahma Kumaris campus. Monsoon (July–September) is lush and misty but the final 30 km hill road can be affected by landslides. Avoid May–June (temperatures milder than Rajasthan plains at 28–35°C but very crowded with domestic tourists escaping the heat)." },
