    intro: "Lansdowne is the answer to everything that is wrong with Mussoorie and Nainital on a holiday weekend. A cantonment town in the Pauri Garhwal district of Uttarakhand at 1,706 m, it was established in 1887 as the headquarters of the Garhwal Rifles regiment and has maintained its character — quiet, oak-forested, almost entirely free of tourist infrastructure — ever since. There are no shopping malls, no tourist restaurants with laminated menus, and no vehicle traffic in the cantonment area. At 265 km from Delhi via NH119, it is one of the closest genuine hill escapes from the capital — 5–6 hours by cab, arriving in a different century.",
    bestTime: { period: "October–June", description: "October to June is pleasant across all seasons. October–November: clear skies, golden oak forests, light trekking weather. December–February: cold (0–10°C) with occasional light snow that stays for 1–2 days — beautiful and peaceful. March–May: mild 15–22°C, rhododendrons blooming in the forests. Monsoon (July–September): very heavy rainfall, some road risk, but the forest is outrageously green. Lansdowne is notably cooler than Dehradun or Mussoorie — the surrounding oak and pine forest keeps temperatures 3–5°C lower." },
